(fifthQuint)Stereotactic Body Radiation Therapy in Treating Patients With Localized High-Risk Prostate Cancer.

 PRIMARY OBJECTIVES: I.

 To establish the efficacy of stereotactic body radiation therapy (SBRT) in patients with high-risk localized prostate cancer compared to historical data from clinical trials.

 II.

 To establish the safety with physician-reported outcomes after SBRT in patients with high risk localized prostate cancer.

 III.

 To establish the quality of life with patient-reported validated questionnaires after SBRT in patients with high risk localized prostate cancer.

 OUTLINE: Patients undergo SBRT daily or every other day for a total of 5 fraction not exceeding 14 consecutive days.

 Patients may also receive androgen deprivation therapy for up to 9 months at the discretion of the treating physician.

 After completion of study treatment, patients are followed up every 4 months for 1 year, every 6 months for 5 years, and then every 12 months thereafter.

